{"title_page": "2007 Formula One espionage controversy", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Spygate (disambiguation){{!}}Spygate}}\n\nThe '''2007 Formula One espionage controversy''', also known as '''Spygate''' and '''Stepneygate''', was a set of accusations among [[Formula One]] racing teams that confidential technical information had been passed between them. It involved the [[McLaren]] team, the [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] team, and the [[Renault F1]] team.\n\nThe original case involved allegations made by the Ferrari Formula One team against a former employee ([[Nigel Stepney]]), a senior McLaren engineer, [[Mike Coughlan]], and his wife Trudy Coughlan concerning the theft of technical information. These allegations were the subject of legal action in Italy and an [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] (FIA) investigation. A [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] case in England was dropped after Ferrari reached an agreement with the Coughlans.\n\nAn FIA hearing into the matter took place on 26 July 2007 but did not result in any penalty for McLaren. However, a second hearing took place on 13 September 2007, and by then, compelling evidence resulted in several penalties for the team. The most important of these were the team's exclusion from the {{F1|2007}} Constructors' Championship and a record-breaking fine of $100 million. Following information from McLaren, allegations were subsequently made during November 2007 by the FIA against the [[Renault F1]] team regarding information they were found to have in their possession concerning the 2006 and 2007 McLaren F1 cars. These allegations were also the subject of an FIA investigation, with a hearing taking place 6 December 2007.\n\n==Background==\nAlong with [[Michael Schumacher]], [[Jean Todt]], [[Ross Brawn]] and [[Rory Byrne]], [[Nigel Stepney]] was part of the \"dream team\" credited with the change of fortunes of Ferrari in the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |first=Adam|last=Cooper|title=Analysis: the remarkable Stepneygate saga |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60467 |work=autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-07-03 |accessdate=2013-06-29 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070707005150/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60467| archivedate= 7 July 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2007, Stepney made public comments regarding his \"unhappiness\" following the team's reorganization which had resulted from Ross Brawn's departure:<ref>{{cite news|title=Unhappy Stepney wants a sabbatical |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/56539 |work=autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-02-01|accessdate=2007-07-11 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070620144720/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/56539| archivedate= 20 June 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{cquote|I am looking at spending a year away from Ferrari, I'm not currently happy with the situation within the team - I really want to move forward with my career and that's something that's not happening right now. Ideally, I'd like to move into a new environment here at Ferrari - but if an opportunity arose with another team, I would definitely consider it.}}\n\nLater that month, Ferrari announced another change in the team structure which saw Stepney appointed as head of Team Performance Development: \"After many years spent working on the Formula One circuits, the last 13 of those as part of the Ferrari Race Team, Nigel Stepney, with the approval of the company, has chosen to take on a different role that will see him no longer have to attend the races.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble|title=Stepney moves in Ferrari reshuffle|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/56889  |work=autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-02-23|accessdate=2007-07-11| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070627042550/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/56889| archivedate= 27 June 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Details==\n\n===Allegations against Stepney===\nIn the week beginning 17 June 2007, at the [[2007 United States Grand Prix]] Ferrari filed a formal complaint against Stepney, leading to the commencement of a criminal investigation by the [[Modena]] district attorney in Italy.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble |author2=Goren, Biranit |title= Ferrari's Stepney faces criminal enquiry |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60025 |work=autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-06-21 |accessdate=2007-07-11 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070625171413/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60025| archivedate= 25 June 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2007, ''[[Gazzetta dello Sport]]'' reported that Ferrari had completed its internal investigation and had dismissed Stepney as a result.<ref name=\"itv dismissal\">{{cite news\n |title=Ferrari dismisses Nigel Stepney \n |url=http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39875 \n |work=www.itv-f1.com \n |publisher=ITV Network \n |date=2007-07-03 \n |accessdate=2007-07-11 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070705205046/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39875 \n |archivedate=5 July 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |df= \n}}</ref> At the same time, Ferrari spokesman Luca Colajanni told ITV Sport that Ferrari\u2019s action against Stepney related to \"irregularities discovered at the Ferrari factory prior to the [[2007 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco Grand Prix]]\".<ref name=\"itv dismissal\"/>\n\n===Allegations against Coughlan===\nOn the day Ferrari announced Stepney\u2019s dismissal, the team also announced it had taken action against \"an engineer from the Vodafone McLaren-Mercedes team\", later named as [[Mike Coughlan]]. Coughlan was suspended by McLaren as a result.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble|author2=Goren, Biranit |title=McLaren suspect is Mike Coughlan |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60466 |work=www.autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-07-03  |accessdate=2007-07-03}}</ref>\n\nA Scuderia Ferrari press release said:<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble|author2=Goren, Biranit |title=Ferrari confirm action against McLaren man|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60465 |work=www.autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-07-03  |accessdate=2007-07-03}}</ref>\n{{cquote|Ferrari announces it has recently presented a case against [[Nigel Stepney]] and an engineer from the Vodafone McLaren-Mercedes team [named by Autosport.com as Coughlan] with the Modena Tribunal, concerning the theft of technical information. Furthermore, legal action has been instigated in England and a search warrant has been issued concerning the engineer. This produced a positive outcome.}}\n\nThe search warrant is understood to have been related to Coughlan's home and the \"positive outcome\" is reported to be documents claimed to have originated at Ferrari's [[Maranello]] factory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planet-f1.com/story/0,18954,3213_2466612,00.html |title='Police raid found Ferrari documents at McLaren designer's home' |work=www.planet-f1.com |publisher=Planet F1 |date=2007-07-04 |accessdate=2007-07-04 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707082823/http://www.planet-f1.com/story/0%2C18954%2C3213_2466612%2C00.html |archivedate=7 July 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Stepney's dismissal from Ferrari had been announced earlier the same day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ferrari dismisses Nigel Stepney |url=http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39875 |work=www.itv-f1.com |publisher=ITV Network |date=2007-07-03 |accessdate=2007-07-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070705205046/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39875 |archivedate=5 July 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 10 July 2007 a High Court hearing was opened and adjourned until the following day, to allow Mike Coughlan to submit an [[affidavit]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Espionage case goes to High Court |url=http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40014 |work=www.itv-f1.com |publisher=ITV Network |date=2007-07-10 |accessdate=2007-07-11 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070712144602/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40014 |archivedate=2007-07-12 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> However, details released include the fact that Mike Coughlan is alleged by Ferrari to be in possession of 780 pages of Ferrari documentation, and that his wife is alleged to have taken them to a photocopying shop near [[Woking]].<ref name=\"High Court day 1\">{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble|author2=Goren, Biranit |title=Spy case court hearing adjourned|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60690 |work=www.autosport.com|publisher=Haymarket|date=2007-07-10|accessdate=2007-07-11| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070712144959/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60690| archivedate= 12 July 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref> Ferrari were unaware that their technical information had been stolen until they received a tip from an employee in the photocopying shop. The staff member saw that the documents were confidential and belonged to Ferrari and, after copying them, decided to contact the team\u2019s headquarters in Italy.<ref name=\"disgraceful\">{{cite news |first= Edward |last= Gorman|title=Coughlan accused of \u2018disgraceful\u2019 behaviour|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/formula_1/article2056456.ece |work=www.timesonline.co.uk|date=2007-07-11|accessdate=2007-09-09 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nCoughlan did not submit the affidavit because of the possibility of it being used against him in an Italian court case.<ref name=\"High Court day 1\"/> However, late on 10 July 2007, Ferrari reached an agreement with Mr. and Mrs. Coughlan under which Ferrari dropped its High Court case in return for their full disclosure of all they know about the case and a promise of future cooperation.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble|author2=Goren, Biranit |title=Ferrari, Coughlans reach agreement |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60706 |work=www.autosport.com|publisher=Haymarket|date=2007-07-11|accessdate=2007-07-11| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070713173612/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60706| archivedate= 13 July 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 July 2007, McLaren announced that its own internal investigation had revealed that \"no Ferrari materials or data are or have ever been in the possession of any McLaren employee other than the individual sued by Ferrari. The fact that he held at his home unsolicited materials from Ferrari was not known to any other member of the team prior to July 3.\"<ref>{{cite news |title =McLaren confirms that Coughlan acted alone |publisher =grandprix.com |url =http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns19408.html |date =2007-07-16 |accessdate =2007-07-17| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070818195129/http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns19408.html| archivedate= 18 August 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Allegations against Renault F1===\n\nOn 8 November 2007, the FIA announced that the [[Renault F1]] team would be summoned before the FIA World Motorsport Council to answer a charge of possession of confidential information relating to the 2006 and 2007 [[McLaren]] [[Formula One]] cars. The statement issued by the FIA states that Renault F1 was found to have information \"including, but not limited to the layout and critical dimensions of the McLaren F1 car, together with details of the McLaren fuelling system, gear assembly, oil cooling system, hydraulic control system and a [[Inerter (mechanical networks)|novel suspension component]] used by the 2006 and 2007 McLaren F1 cars\". The date for the hearing was set for 6 December 2007.<ref name='renaultf1spy2'>{{cite web |url=http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Releases/FIA_Sport/2007/November/081107-01.html |title=World Motor Sport Council |accessdate=2007-11-08 |date=2007-11-08 |publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109183349/http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Releases/FIA_Sport/2007/November/081107-01.html |archivedate=2007-11-09 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The espionage claims are thought to revolve around an employee, Philip Mackereth, who transferred from McLaren to Renault, according to FIA President [[Max Mosley]].<ref name='renaultf1spy1'>{{cite news | first= Andrew| last= Benson| title=Renault face McLaren spy charge | date=2007-11-08 | publisher=BBC | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/7085098.stm | work =BBC News Online | pages = | accessdate = 2007-11-08 | language = | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071110030719/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/7085098.stm| archivedate= 10 November 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===FIA investigation===\nOn 4 July 2007, McLaren announced it had conducted an investigation and concluded that \"no Ferrari intellectual property has been passed to any other members of the team or incorporated into [our] cars.\" The team also invited the FIA to inspect its cars to confirm these facts; \"In order to address some of the speculation McLaren has invited the FIA to conduct a full review of its cars to satisfy itself that the team has not benefited from any intellectual property of another competitor.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=McLaren moves to allay spy case concerns |url=http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39899 |work=www.itv-f1.com |publisher=ITV Network |date=2007-07-04 |accessdate=2007-07-04 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707010627/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39899 |archivedate=2007-07-07 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Since the revelation of Coughlan's involvement in the affair, McLaren provided a full set of drawings and development documents to the FIA, detailing all updates made to the [[McLaren MP4-22|team's chassis]] since the incident occurred at the end of April.<ref name=\"hondastepney\">{{cite news|title=Honda was approached by spy suspects |url=http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39942 |work=www.itv-f1.com |publisher=ITV Network |date=2007-07-06 |accessdate=2007-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708184404/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39942 |archivedate=2007-07-08 |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 12 July 2007, the FIA announced that it had summoned McLaren to an extraordinary meeting of the FIA World Motor Sport Council to answer charges that they had breached Article 151C of the International Sporting Code.<ref>{{cite news |title=FIA summons McLaren in spy case  |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60729 |work=www.autosport.com |publisher=Autosport |date= 2007-07-12 |accessdate=2007-07-12| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070714220154/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60729| archivedate= 14 July 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref> At the hearing on 26 July 2007, FIA found that Vodafone McLaren-Mercedes was in possession of confidential Ferrari information and is therefore in breach of the Code, but with no evidence that they had used the information no punishment was levied. However, the FIA reserved the right to reconvene on the matter if any such evidence subsequently came to light.<ref>{{cite news| title =FIA imposes no penalty on McLaren| publisher =autosport.com| url =http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/61155| date =2007-07-26| accessdate =2007-07-26}}</ref>\n\nFerrari labelled the decision \"incomprehensible\"; ''[[Autosport]]'' judged the team to be \"furious\".<ref>{{cite news| first = Pablo| last = Elizalde| title = Ferrari furious with McLaren's reprieve| url = http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/61159| work = Autosport| publisher = Haymarket| date = 2007-07-26| accessdate = 2007-07-26}}\n</ref> McLaren said \"[a] unanimous decision has been taken by the FIA which in McLaren's opinion is very balanced and fair.\"<ref>{{cite news| title =McLaren say decision 'balanced and fair' | publisher =autosport.com| url =http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/61162| date =2007-07-26| accessdate =2007-07-26}}</ref> The matter was referred to the [[FIA International Court of Appeal]], with the hearing scheduled for 13 September 2007.<ref name=\"ICA date\">{{cite news| title =Appeal date is September 13| publisher =grandprix.com| url =http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns19516.html| date =2007-08-07| accessdate =2007-08-08| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070820071700/http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns19516.html| archivedate= 20 August 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 August 2007, Ron Dennis, in an open letter to the president of the Italian motorsport authority Luigi Macaluso, accused Ferrari of giving a false and dishonest version of events and further that the car used to win the [[2007 Australian Grand Prix]] was illegal.<ref>[http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40222 McLaren hits back at Ferrari] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927000757/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40222 |date=September 27, 2007 }}.</ref> McLaren learned of the \"illegal\" floor device from Nigel Stepney, with the team describing this contact as whistle-blowing. However the team insists that following this incident, Jonathan Neale instructed Coughlan to cease contact with Stepney. McLaren accuse Ferrari of trying to blur this \"whistle-blowing\" of which McLaren was aware, with Coughlan's possession of the 780 page Ferrari dossier of which it insists it was not aware.<ref>[http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/61260 McLaren hit out at Ferrari]</ref>\n\nThe [[2007 Hungarian Grand Prix]] was a controversial weekend for McLaren; Hamilton had disobeyed a team instruction, disadvantaging Alonso, and so Alonso held Hamilton up in the pit lane during qualifying, denying Hamilton a chance to record a final lap time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Was Dennis to blame in McLaren\u2019s Hungary row? |publisher=f1fanatic.co.uk|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2008/02/04/was-dennis-to-blame-in-mclarens-hungary-row/|date=2008-02-04 |accessdate=2017-09-01 |first=Keith |last=Collantine |df= }}</ref> In the following discord within the team, TV pictures showed Ron Dennis angrily throwing his headphones down as Alonso pulled out of the pits, and after the session was over he was then shown having a serious conversation with Alonso's trainer. On the morning of the race (August 5), Alonso met Ron Dennis in his motorhome and allegedly threatened to send his email exchanges with McLaren test driver [[Pedro de la Rosa]] and Coughlan to the FIA. According to [[Max Mosley]], Ron Dennis informed him of the conversation and told Mosley that the threat was an empty one, \"There's no information, there's nothing to come out; I can assure you that if there was something, Max, I would have told you.\u201d Mosley subsequently retracted the implication that Dennis had lied.<ref>{{cite news| title =Mosley and Dennis clear the air | publisher =autosport.com| url =http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/62438| date =2007-09-15| accessdate =2007-09-15| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071023012427/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/62438| archivedate= 23 October 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2007, the FIA announced that it had received new evidence regarding the case, and would re-open the investigation on September 13. This replaced the planned appeal hearing.<ref name=\"reopen\">{{cite news| title =FIA: Spy case to be heard again| publisher =itv-f1.com| url =http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40524| date =2007-09-05| accessdate =2007-09-05| url-status=dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070908065955/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40524| archivedate =2007-09-08| df =}}</ref> It later transpired that the new evidence was the driver's emails that were sent to Bernie Ecclestone, F1's commercial rights holder who then informed the FIA.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mosley admits Ecclestone told him of McLaren emails |publisher=Guardian Online |url=http://sport.guardian.co.uk/motorsport/story/0,,2177259,00.html |date=2007-09-26 |accessdate=2007-09-26 |location=London |first=Alan |last=Henry |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016170640/http://sport.guardian.co.uk/motorsport/story/0%2C%2C2177259%2C00.html |archivedate=16 October 2007 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> \nThe FIA requested the three McLaren drivers (Alonso, Hamilton, and de la Rosa) to provide relevant evidence and help the FIA in further investigation. In return, the FIA offered assurance that any information made available would not result in any proceeding against the driver personally under the International Sporting Code or the Formula One Regulations. However, the drivers were notified that if it later came to light that they had withheld any potentially relevant information, serious consequences could follow.<ref name=\"FIA press release\">{{cite press release|title=Re: Article 151(c) International Sporting Code \u2013 Vodafone McLaren Mercedes |publisher=World Motor Sports council |url=http://www.fia.com/resources/documents/17844641__WMSC_Decision_130907.pdf |format=PDF |date=2007-09-13 |accessdate=14 September 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022060508/http://www.fia.com/resources/documents/17844641__WMSC_Decision_130907.pdf |archivedate=22 October 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 September, McLaren approached the FIA with questions about the [[Renault F1]] team, and possibly other (then unknown teams) as well. At the time, it was unknown if the meeting related directly to the espionage scandal, but a key McLaren argument made was that if McLaren was guilty, other teams were as well.<ref>{{cite news| title =FIA: McLaren have queried Renault \n| publisher =autosport.com| url =http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/62274| date =2007-09-11| accessdate =2007-09-11| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070914194753/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/62274| archivedate= 14 September 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 September, the FIA hearing imposed a penalty for illicitly collecting and holding information from Ferrari to confer a dishonest and fraudulent sporting advantage upon McLaren. The penalty consisted of exclusion from and withdrawal of all points awarded to McLaren in all rounds of the 2007 Constructors' Championship, a record fine of $100 million (less the TV and travel income lost as a result of the points deduction), and the obligation for the team to submit its {{F1|2008}} chassis for scrutiny.  However, [[Fernando Alonso]] and [[Lewis Hamilton]]'s points were not affected, and the two were free to contest the Drivers' Championship, because McLaren's drivers were offered immunity in exchange for cooperation. The team was not banned and all drivers points earned only counted towards the driver's championship points. Whenever a McLaren driver won any of the remaining races, (the only example being Hamilton at the [[2007 Japanese Grand Prix|Japanese Grand Prix]]), no McLaren representative was allowed onto the podium.<ref name=\"penalty\">{{cite news| title =McLaren hit with constructors' ban| publisher =news.bbc.co.uk| url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/6991147.stm| date =2007-09-13| accessdate =2007-09-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 September, Ron Dennis announced that he was the one who alerted the FIA that further evidence existed.\n\nOn 15 September, Max Mosley contested Ron Dennis' claim that he alerted the FIA to the existence of further evidence, claiming that Dennis actually alerted him that Alonso had decided to send the emails in himself, and that Mosley had been erroneously assured by Dennis that the emails contained nothing incriminating.\n\nOn 6 December, Renault were found guilty of breaching article 151(c) of the International Sporting Code by another FIA WMSC hearing, but escaped penalty.<ref name=\"renault decision\">{{cite news| url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/64302| title=Renault found guilty but not penalised| author=Jonathan Noble| accessdate=2007-12-06| date=2007-12-06| work=Autosport.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080116221701/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/64302| archivedate= 16 January 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 December, McLaren issued a press release detailing a letter sent by [[Martin Whitmarsh]], COO of the team, to the FIA.<ref name=\"13decmclarenrelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mclaren.com/latestnews/press-releases-2007.php?article=60|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214072736/http://www.mclaren.com/latestnews/press-releases-2007.php?article=60|archivedate=2007-12-14|title=McLaren Statement - 13th December 2007|accessdate=2007-12-15}}</ref>  In the letter, Whitmarsh stated that the team accepted that \"a number of McLaren employees\" had access to Ferrari technical information, and apologised that it took the intervention of the FIA for this to come to light. The team also offered to \"enter into discussion... as to a moratorium of an appropriate length in respect of the use\" of the systems.<ref name=\"whitmarshletter\">{{Cite web\n  | last = Whitmarsh\n  | first = Martin\n  | authorlink = Martin Whitmarsh\n  | title = Letter from the COO of McLaren to the FIA - 05.12.2007\n  | date = 2007-12-05\n  | url = http://www.mclaren.com/latestnews/pdf/Max-Mosley-and-WMSC-members.pdf\n  |format=PDF| accessdate = 2007-12-15\n  | postscript = <!--None--> }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}{{cbignore}} \n</ref>  On the same day, the FIA issued a press release stating that the FIA president would ask the members of the World Council \"for their consent to cancel the hearing scheduled for 14 February 2008 and, in the interests of the sport, to consider this matter closed.\" <ref name=\"13decfiarelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Releases/FIA_Sport/2007/December/131207-01.html |title=McLaren Apology and Undertakings |accessdate=2007-12-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214175714/http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Releases/FIA_Sport/2007/December/131207-01.html |archivedate=14 December 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February 2009, legal proceedings against McLaren employees in Italy were dropped. In return, Mike Coughlan had to pay \u20ac180,000 while three employees of McLaren ([[Paddy Lowe]], [[Jonathan Neale]] and Rob Taylor) had to pay \u20ac150,000.<ref name=\"chargesdropped\">{{cite news| title =McLaren 'spy' case ended in Italy| publisher =www.itv-f1.com/| url =http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?id=45154| date =2009-02-23| accessdate =2009-02-24| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090226131741/http://www.itv-f1.com/news_article.aspx?id=45154| archivedate =2009-02-26| url-status=dead| df =}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071004034002/http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Releases/FIA_Sport/2007/September/190907-01.html World Motor Sport Council Transcripts from 26 July 2007 and 13 September 2007]\n\n[[Category:2007 in Formula One|Espionage controversy]]\n[[Category:Espionage scandals and incidents|Formula]]\n[[Category:Formula One controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Spygate (disambiguation){{!}}Spygate}}\n\nThe '''2007 Formula One espionage controversy''', also known as '''Spygate''' and '''Stepneygate''', was a set of accusations among [[Formula One]] racing teams that confidential technical information had been passed between them. It involved the [[McLaren]] team, the [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] team, and the [[Renault F1]] team.\n\nThe original case involved allegations made by the Ferrari Formula One team against a former employee ([[Nigel Stepney]]), a senior McLaren engineer, [[Mike Coughlan]], and his wife Trudy Coughlan concerning the theft of technical information. These allegations were the subject of legal action in Italy and an [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]] (FIA) investigation. A [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] case in England was dropped after Ferrari reached an agreement with the Coughlans.\n\nAn FIA hearing into the matter took place on 26 July 2007 but did not result in any penalty for McLaren. However, a second hearing took place on 13 September 2007, and by then, compelling evidence resulted in several penalties for the team. The most important of these were the team's exclusion from the {{F1|2007}} Constructors' Championship and a record-breaking fine of $100 million. Following information from McLaren, allegations were subsequently made during November 2007 by the FIA against the [[Renault F1]] team regarding information they were found to have in their possession concerning the 2006 and 2007 McLaren F1 cars. These allegations were also the subject of an FIA investigation, with a hearing taking place 6 December 2007.\n\n==Background==\nAlong with [[Michael Schumacher]], [[Jean Todt]], [[Ross Brawn]] and [[Rory Byrne]], [[Nigel Stepney]] was part of the \"dream team\" credited with the change of fortunes of Ferrari in the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |first=Adam|last=Cooper|title=Analysis: the remarkable Stepneygate saga |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60467 |work=autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-07-03 |accessdate=2013-06-29 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070707005150/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60467| archivedate= 7 July 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2007, Stepney made public comments regarding his \"unhappiness\" following the team's reorganization which had resulted from Ross Brawn's departure:<ref>{{cite news|title=Unhappy Stepney wants a sabbatical |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/56539 |work=autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-02-01|accessdate=2007-07-11 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070620144720/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/56539| archivedate= 20 June 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{cquote|I am looking at spending a year away from Ferrari, I'm not currently happy with the situation within the team - I really want to move forward with my career and that's something that's not happening right now. Ideally, I'd like to move into a new environment here at Ferrari - but if an opportunity arose with another team, I would definitely consider it.}}\n\nLater that month, Ferrari announced another change in the team structure which saw Stepney appointed as head of Team Performance Development: \"After many years spent working on the Formula One circuits, the last 13 of those as part of the Ferrari Race Team, Nigel Stepney, with the approval of the company, has chosen to take on a different role that will see him no longer have to attend the races.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble|title=Stepney moves in Ferrari reshuffle|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/56889  |work=autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-02-23|accessdate=2007-07-11| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070627042550/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/56889| archivedate= 27 June 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Details==\n\n===Allegations against Stepney===\nIn the week beginning 17 June 2007, at the [[2007 United States Grand Prix]] Ferrari filed a formal complaint against Stepney, leading to the commencement of a criminal investigation by the [[Modena]] district attorney in Italy.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble |author2=Goren, Biranit |title= Ferrari's Stepney faces criminal enquiry |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60025 |work=autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-06-21 |accessdate=2007-07-11 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070625171413/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60025| archivedate= 25 June 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 July 2007, ''[[Gazzetta dello Sport]]'' reported that Ferrari had completed its internal investigation and had dismissed Stepney as a result.<ref name=\"itv dismissal\">{{cite news\n |title=Ferrari dismisses Nigel Stepney \n |url=http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39875 \n |work=www.itv-f1.com \n |publisher=ITV Network \n |date=2007-07-03 \n |accessdate=2007-07-11 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070705205046/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39875 \n |archivedate=5 July 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |df= \n}}</ref> At the same time, Ferrari spokesman Luca Colajanni told ITV Sport that Ferrari\u2019s action against Stepney related to \"irregularities discovered at the Ferrari factory prior to the [[2007 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco Grand Prix]]\".<ref name=\"itv dismissal\"/>\n\n===Allegations against Coughlan===\nOn the day Ferrari announced Stepney\u2019s dismissal, the team also announced it had taken action against \"an engineer from the Vodafone McLaren-Mercedes team\", later named as [[Mike Coughlan]]. Coughlan was suspended by McLaren as a result.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble|author2=Goren, Biranit |title=McLaren suspect is Mike Coughlan |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60466 |work=www.autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-07-03  |accessdate=2007-07-03}}</ref>\n\nA Scuderia Ferrari press release said:<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble|author2=Goren, Biranit |title=Ferrari confirm action against McLaren man|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60465 |work=www.autosport.com |publisher=Haymarket |date=2007-07-03  |accessdate=2007-07-03}}</ref>\n{{cquote|Ferrari announces it has recently presented a case against [[Nigel Stepney]] and an engineer from the Vodafone McLaren-Mercedes team [named by Autosport.com as Coughlan] with the Modena Tribunal, concerning the theft of technical information. Furthermore, legal action has been instigated in England and a search warrant has been issued concerning the engineer. This produced a positive outcome.}}\n\nThe search warrant is understood to have been related to Coughlan's home and the \"positive outcome\" is reported to be documents claimed to have originated at Ferrari's [[Maranello]] factory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planet-f1.com/story/0,18954,3213_2466612,00.html |title='Police raid found Ferrari documents at McLaren designer's home' |work=www.planet-f1.com |publisher=Planet F1 |date=2007-07-04 |accessdate=2007-07-04 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707082823/http://www.planet-f1.com/story/0%2C18954%2C3213_2466612%2C00.html |archivedate=7 July 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Stepney's dismissal from Ferrari had been announced earlier the same day.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ferrari dismisses Nigel Stepney |url=http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39875 |work=www.itv-f1.com |publisher=ITV Network |date=2007-07-03 |accessdate=2007-07-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070705205046/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39875 |archivedate=5 July 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 10 July 2007 a High Court hearing was opened and adjourned until the following day, to allow Mike Coughlan to submit an [[affidavit]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Espionage case goes to High Court |url=http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40014 |work=www.itv-f1.com |publisher=ITV Network |date=2007-07-10 |accessdate=2007-07-11 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070712144602/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40014 |archivedate=2007-07-12 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> However, details released include the fact that Mike Coughlan is alleged by Ferrari to be in possession of 780 pages of Ferrari documentation, and that his wife is alleged to have taken them to a photocopying shop near [[Woking]].<ref name=\"High Court day 1\">{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble|author2=Goren, Biranit |title=Spy case court hearing adjourned|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60690 |work=www.autosport.com|publisher=Haymarket|date=2007-07-10|accessdate=2007-07-11| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070712144959/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60690| archivedate= 12 July 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref> Ferrari were unaware that their technical information had been stolen until they received a tip from an employee in the photocopying shop. The staff member saw that the documents were confidential and belonged to Ferrari and, after copying them, decided to contact the team\u2019s headquarters in Italy.<ref name=\"disgraceful\">{{cite news |first= Edward |last= Gorman|title=Coughlan accused of \u2018disgraceful\u2019 behaviour|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/formula_1/article2056456.ece |work=www.timesonline.co.uk|date=2007-07-11|accessdate=2007-09-09 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nCoughlan did not submit the affidavit because of the possibility of it being used against him in an Italian court case.<ref name=\"High Court day 1\"/> However, late on 10 July 2007, Ferrari reached an agreement with Mr. and Mrs. Coughlan under which Ferrari dropped its High Court case in return for their full disclosure of all they know about the case and a promise of future cooperation.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jonathan |last=Noble|author2=Goren, Biranit |title=Ferrari, Coughlans reach agreement |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60706 |work=www.autosport.com|publisher=Haymarket|date=2007-07-11|accessdate=2007-07-11| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070713173612/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60706| archivedate= 13 July 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 July 2007, McLaren announced that its own internal investigation had revealed that \"no Ferrari materials or data are or have ever been in the possession of any McLaren employee other than the individual sued by Ferrari. The fact that he held at his home unsolicited materials from Ferrari was not known to any other member of the team prior to July 3.\"<ref>{{cite news |title =McLaren confirms that Coughlan acted alone |publisher =grandprix.com |url =http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns19408.html |date =2007-07-16 |accessdate =2007-07-17| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070818195129/http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns19408.html| archivedate= 18 August 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Allegations against Renault F1===\n\nOn 8 November 2007, the FIA announced that the [[Renault F1]] team would be summoned before the FIA World Motorsport Council to answer a charge of possession of confidential information relating to the 2006 and 2007 [[McLaren]] [[Formula One]] cars. The statement issued by the FIA states that Renault F1 was found to have information \"including, but not limited to the layout and critical dimensions of the McLaren F1 car, together with details of the McLaren fuelling system, gear assembly, oil cooling system, hydraulic control system and a [[Inerter (mechanical networks)|novel suspension component]] used by the 2006 and 2007 McLaren F1 cars\". The date for the hearing was set for 6 December 2007.<ref name='renaultf1spy2'>{{cite web |url=http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Releases/FIA_Sport/2007/November/081107-01.html |title=World Motor Sport Council |accessdate=2007-11-08 |date=2007-11-08 |publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109183349/http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Releases/FIA_Sport/2007/November/081107-01.html |archivedate=2007-11-09 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The espionage claims are thought to revolve around an employee, Philip Mackereth, who transferred from McLaren to Renault, according to FIA President [[Max Mosley]].<ref name='renaultf1spy1'>{{cite news | first= Andrew| last= Benson| title=Renault face McLaren spy charge | date=2007-11-08 | publisher=BBC | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/7085098.stm | work =BBC News Online | pages = | accessdate = 2007-11-08 | language = | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071110030719/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/7085098.stm| archivedate= 10 November 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===FIA investigation===\nOn 4 July 2007, McLaren announced it had conducted an investigation and concluded that \"no Ferrari intellectual property has been passed to any other members of the team or incorporated into [our] cars.\" The team also invited the FIA to inspect its cars to confirm these facts; \"In order to address some of the speculation McLaren has invited the FIA to conduct a full review of its cars to satisfy itself that the team has not benefited from any intellectual property of another competitor.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=McLaren moves to allay spy case concerns |url=http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39899 |work=www.itv-f1.com |publisher=ITV Network |date=2007-07-04 |accessdate=2007-07-04 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707010627/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39899 |archivedate=2007-07-07 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Since the revelation of Coughlan's involvement in the affair, McLaren provided a full set of drawings and development documents to the FIA, detailing all updates made to the [[McLaren MP4-22|team's chassis]] since the incident occurred at the end of April.<ref name=\"hondastepney\">{{cite news|title=Honda was approached by spy suspects |url=http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39942 |work=www.itv-f1.com |publisher=ITV Network |date=2007-07-06 |accessdate=2007-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708184404/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=39942 |archivedate=2007-07-08 |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 12 July 2007, the FIA announced that it had summoned McLaren to an extraordinary meeting of the FIA World Motor Sport Council to answer charges that they had breached Article 151C of the International Sporting Code.<ref>{{cite news |title=FIA summons McLaren in spy case  |url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60729 |work=www.autosport.com |publisher=Autosport |date= 2007-07-12 |accessdate=2007-07-12| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070714220154/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/60729| archivedate= 14 July 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref> At the hearing on 26 July 2007, FIA found that Vodafone McLaren-Mercedes was in possession of confidential Ferrari information and is therefore in breach of the Code, but with no evidence that they had used the information no punishment was levied. However, the FIA reserved the right to reconvene on the matter if any such evidence subsequently came to light.<ref>{{cite news| title =FIA imposes no penalty on McLaren| publisher =autosport.com| url =http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/61155| date =2007-07-26| accessdate =2007-07-26}}</ref>\n\nFerrari labelled the decision \"incomprehensible\"; ''[[Autosport]]'' judged the team to be \"furious\".<ref>{{cite news| first = Pablo| last = Elizalde| title = Ferrari furious with McLaren's reprieve| url = http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/61159| work = Autosport| publisher = Haymarket| date = 2007-07-26| accessdate = 2007-07-26}}\n</ref> McLaren said \"[a] unanimous decision has been taken by the FIA which in McLaren's opinion is very balanced and fair.\"<ref>{{cite news| title =McLaren say decision 'balanced and fair' | publisher =autosport.com| url =http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/61162| date =2007-07-26| accessdate =2007-07-26}}</ref> The matter was referred to the [[FIA International Court of Appeal]], with the hearing scheduled for 13 September 2007.<ref name=\"ICA date\">{{cite news| title =Appeal date is September 13| publisher =grandprix.com| url =http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns19516.html| date =2007-08-07| accessdate =2007-08-08| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070820071700/http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns19516.html| archivedate= 20 August 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 August 2007, Ron Dennis, in an open letter to the president of the Italian motorsport authority Luigi Macaluso, accused Ferrari of giving a false and dishonest version of events and further that the car used to win the [[2007 Australian Grand Prix]] was illegal.<ref>[http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40222 McLaren hits back at Ferrari] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927000757/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40222 |date=September 27, 2007 }}.</ref> McLaren learned of the \"illegal\" floor device from Nigel Stepney, with the team describing this contact as whistle-blowing. However the team insists that following this incident, Jonathan Neale instructed Coughlan to cease contact with Stepney. McLaren accuse Ferrari of trying to blur this \"whistle-blowing\" of which McLaren was aware, with Coughlan's possession of the 780 page Ferrari dossier of which it insists it was not aware.<ref>[http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/61260 McLaren hit out at Ferrari]</ref>\n\nThe [[2007 Hungarian Grand Prix]] was a controversial weekend for McLaren; Hamilton had disobeyed a team instruction, disadvantaging Alonso, and so Alonso held Hamilton up in the pit lane during qualifying, denying Hamilton a chance to record a final lap time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Was Dennis to blame in McLaren\u2019s Hungary row? |publisher=f1fanatic.co.uk|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2008/02/04/was-dennis-to-blame-in-mclarens-hungary-row/|date=2008-02-04 |accessdate=2017-09-01 |first=Keith |last=Collantine |df= }}</ref> In the following discord within the team, TV pictures showed Ron Dennis angrily throwing his headphones down as Alonso pulled out of the pits, and after the session was over he was then shown having a serious conversation with Alonso's trainer. On the morning of the race (August 5), Alonso met Ron Dennis in his motorhome and allegedly threatened to send his email exchanges with McLaren test driver [[Pedro de la Rosa]] and Coughlan to the FIA. According to [[Max Mosley]], Ron Dennis informed him of the conversation and told Mosley that the threat was an empty one, \"There's no information, there's nothing to come out; I can assure you that if there was something, Max, I would have told you.\u201d Mosley subsequently retracted the implication that Dennis had lied.<ref>{{cite news| title =Mosley and Dennis clear the air | publisher =autosport.com| url =http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/62438| date =2007-09-15| accessdate =2007-09-15| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071023012427/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/62438| archivedate= 23 October 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 September 2007, the FIA announced that it had received new evidence regarding the case, and would re-open the investigation on September 13. This replaced the planned appeal hearing.<ref name=\"reopen\">{{cite news| title =FIA: Spy case to be heard again| publisher =itv-f1.com| url =http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40524| date =2007-09-05| accessdate =2007-09-05| url-status=dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20070908065955/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=40524| archivedate =2007-09-08| df =}}</ref> It later transpired that the new evidence was the driver's emails that were sent to Bernie Ecclestone, F1's commercial rights holder who then informed the FIA.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mosley admits Ecclestone told him of McLaren emails |publisher=Guardian Online |url=http://sport.guardian.co.uk/motorsport/story/0,,2177259,00.html |date=2007-09-26 |accessdate=2007-09-26 |location=London |first=Alan |last=Henry |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016170640/http://sport.guardian.co.uk/motorsport/story/0%2C%2C2177259%2C00.html |archivedate=16 October 2007 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> \nThe FIA requested the three McLaren drivers (Alonso, Hamilton, and de la Rosa) to provide relevant evidence and help FIA in further investigation. In return FIA offered assurance that any information made available would not result in any proceeding against the driver personally under the International Sporting Code or the Formula One Regulations. However, the drivers were notified that if it later came to light that they had withheld any potentially relevant information, serious consequences could follow.<ref name=\"FIA press release\">{{cite press release|title=Re: Article 151(c) International Sporting Code \u2013 Vodafone McLaren Mercedes |publisher=World Motor Sports council |url=http://www.fia.com/resources/documents/17844641__WMSC_Decision_130907.pdf |format=PDF |date=2007-09-13 |accessdate=14 September 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022060508/http://www.fia.com/resources/documents/17844641__WMSC_Decision_130907.pdf |archivedate=22 October 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 September, McLaren approached the FIA with questions about the [[Renault F1]] team, and possibly other (then unknown teams) as well. At the time, it was unknown if the meeting related directly to the espionage scandal, but a key McLaren argument made was that if McLaren was guilty, other teams were as well.<ref>{{cite news| title =FIA: McLaren have queried Renault \n| publisher =autosport.com| url =http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/62274| date =2007-09-11| accessdate =2007-09-11| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070914194753/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/62274| archivedate= 14 September 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 September, the FIA hearing imposed a penalty for illicitly collecting and holding information from Ferrari to confer a dishonest and fraudulent sporting advantage upon McLaren. The penalty consisted of exclusion from and withdrawal of all points awarded to McLaren in all rounds of the 2007 Constructors' Championship, a record fine of $100 million (less the TV and travel income lost as a result of the points deduction), and the obligation for the team to submit its {{F1|2008}} chassis for scrutiny.  However, [[Fernando Alonso]] and [[Lewis Hamilton]]'s points were not affected, and the two were free to contest the Drivers' Championship, because McLaren's drivers were offered immunity in exchange for cooperation. The team was not banned and all drivers points earned only counted towards the driver's championship points. Whenever a McLaren driver won any of the remaining races, (the only example being Hamilton at the [[2007 Japanese Grand Prix|Japanese Grand Prix]]), no McLaren representative was allowed onto the podium.<ref name=\"penalty\">{{cite news| title =McLaren hit with constructors' ban| publisher =news.bbc.co.uk| url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/6991147.stm| date =2007-09-13| accessdate =2007-09-13}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 September, Ron Dennis announced that he was the one who alerted the FIA that further evidence existed.\n\nOn 15 September, Max Mosley contested Ron Dennis' claim that he alerted the FIA to the existence of further evidence, claiming that Dennis actually alerted him that Alonso had decided to send the emails in himself, and that Mosley had been erroneously assured by Dennis that the emails contained nothing incriminating.\n\nOn 6 December, Renault were found guilty of breaching article 151(c) of the International Sporting Code by another FIA WMSC hearing, but escaped penalty.<ref name=\"renault decision\">{{cite news| url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/64302| title=Renault found guilty but not penalised| author=Jonathan Noble| accessdate=2007-12-06| date=2007-12-06| work=Autosport.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080116221701/http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/64302| archivedate= 16 January 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 December, McLaren issued a press release detailing a letter sent by [[Martin Whitmarsh]], COO of the team, to the FIA.<ref name=\"13decmclarenrelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mclaren.com/latestnews/press-releases-2007.php?article=60|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214072736/http://www.mclaren.com/latestnews/press-releases-2007.php?article=60|archivedate=2007-12-14|title=McLaren Statement - 13th December 2007|accessdate=2007-12-15}}</ref>  In the letter, Whitmarsh stated that the team accepted that \"a number of McLaren employees\" had access to Ferrari technical information, and apologised that it took the intervention of the FIA for this to come to light. The team also offered to \"enter into discussion... as to a moratorium of an appropriate length in respect of the use\" of the systems.<ref name=\"whitmarshletter\">{{Cite web\n  | last = Whitmarsh\n  | first = Martin\n  | authorlink = Martin Whitmarsh\n  | title = Letter from the COO of McLaren to the FIA - 05.12.2007\n  | date = 2007-12-05\n  | url = http://www.mclaren.com/latestnews/pdf/Max-Mosley-and-WMSC-members.pdf\n  |format=PDF| accessdate = 2007-12-15\n  | postscript = <!--None--> }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}{{cbignore}} \n</ref>  On the same day, the FIA issued a press release stating that the FIA president would ask the members of the World Council \"for their consent to cancel the hearing scheduled for 14 February 2008 and, in the interests of the sport, to consider this matter closed.\" <ref name=\"13decfiarelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Releases/FIA_Sport/2007/December/131207-01.html |title=McLaren Apology and Undertakings |accessdate=2007-12-15 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214175714/http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Releases/FIA_Sport/2007/December/131207-01.html |archivedate=14 December 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February 2009, legal proceedings against McLaren employees in Italy were dropped. In return, Mike Coughlan had to pay \u20ac180,000 while three employees of McLaren ([[Paddy Lowe]], [[Jonathan Neale]] and Rob Taylor) had to pay \u20ac150,000.<ref name=\"chargesdropped\">{{cite news| title =McLaren 'spy' case ended in Italy| publisher =www.itv-f1.com/| url =http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?id=45154| date =2009-02-23| accessdate =2009-02-24| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20090226131741/http://www.itv-f1.com/news_article.aspx?id=45154| archivedate =2009-02-26| url-status=dead| df =}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071004034002/http://www.fia.com/mediacentre/Press_Releases/FIA_Sport/2007/September/190907-01.html World Motor Sport Council Transcripts from 26 July 2007 and 13 September 2007]\n\n[[Category:2007 in Formula One|Espionage controversy]]\n[[Category:Espionage scandals and incidents|Formula]]\n[[Category:Formula One controversies]]\n", "name_user": "Chrism", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFIA investigation:definite articles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_Formula_One_espionage_controversy"}
{"title_page": "Bids for the 1996 Summer Olympics", "text_new": "{{Infobox Olympic bid|1996|Summer|\n| main = yes\n| Paralympics = yes\n| logo = Atlanta 1996 Olympic bid logo.png\n| logo-size = 175px\n| winner = Atlanta\n| votes1 = 51\n| runner-up = Athens\n| votes2 = 35\n| shortlisted1 = Toronto\n| shortlisted2 = Melbourne\n| shortlisted3 = Manchester\n| shortlisted4 = Belgrade\n| decision = September 18, 1990\n}}\n{{1996 Summer Olympics}}\nSix cities submitted '''bids to host the [[1996 Summer Olympics]]''' (formally known as ''Games of the XXVI Olympiad''), which were awarded to [[Atlanta]], on September 18, 1990. The other candidate cities were [[Athens]] ([[Greece]]), [[Toronto]] ([[Canada]]), [[Melbourne]] ([[Australia]]), [[Manchester]] ([[United Kingdom]]) and [[Belgrade]] ([[FR Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]).\n\n==Results==\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!colspan=7 align=center| 1996 Host City Election \u2014 ballot results\n|-\n! City\n! Country (NOC)\n|bgcolor=silver| '''Round 1'''\n|bgcolor=silver| '''Round 2'''\n|bgcolor=silver| '''Round 3'''\n|bgcolor=silver| '''Round 4'''\n|bgcolor=silver| '''Round 5'''\n|-\n| [[Atlanta]] || {{flag|United States}} || 19 || 20 || '''26''' || '''34''' || '''51'''\n|-\n| [[Athens]] || {{flag|Greece}} || '''23''' || '''23''' || '''26''' || 30 || 35\n|-\n| [[Toronto]] || {{flag|Canada}} || 14 || 17 || 18 || 22 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[Melbourne]] || {{flag|Australia}} || 12 || 21 || 16 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[Manchester]] || {{flag|Great Britain}} || 11 || 5 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[Belgrade]] || {{flag|SFR Yugoslavia}}<ref>The Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia was still in existence at the time of bidding for the 1996 Olympics, although it would cease to exist by the time of the 1996 Summer Olympic games</ref> || 7 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|}\n\n==Background==\nAtlanta was selected by the [[United States Olympic Committee|USOC]] over bids from [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[San Francisco]] and runner-up [[Minneapolis]] to be the U.S. representative in international bidding.<ref name=NewYorkTimes88>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/03/29/sports/sports-people-cities-named.html|title=Cities Named|last=|first=|date=1988-03-29|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2012-08-30}}</ref> The city entered the competition as a [[dark horse]], being up against stiff competition.<ref name=Payne>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vqtLnCWHDX0C&pg=PA91 |title=Olympic turnaround: how the Olympic Games stepped back from the brink of Extinction to Become the Best Known Brand|first=Michael|last=Payne|isbn=0-275-99030-3|location=Westport, Ct.|publisher=Praeger Publishers|year=2006}}</ref> The US media also criticized it as a second-tier city and complained of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia's]] [[Georgia in the American Civil War|Confederate history]]. However, the IOC Evaluation Commission ranked Atlanta's infrastructure and facilities the highest, while IOC members said that it could guarantee large television revenues similar to the success of the [[1984 Summer Olympics]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=NewYorkTimes90/> Additionally, former US ambassador to the UN and Atlanta mayor [[Andrew Jackson Young]] touted Atlanta's civil rights history and reputation for racial harmony. Young also wanted to showcase a reformed [[Southern United States|American South]]. The strong economy of Atlanta and improved race relations in the South helped to impress the IOC officials.<ref name=\"Atlanta 1996\">{{cite book|last=Maloney|first=Larry|title=Encyclopedia of the Modern Olympic Movement|editor=Finding, John E. |editor2=Pelle, Kimberly D. |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2004|pages=235\u20136|chapter=Atlanta 1996|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmXi_-Jujj0C&pg=PA236&lpg=PA236&dq=Atlanta+Athens+IOC+bid&source=web&ots=iX4T-9nx6u&sig=N3lyOoVFskaPnXZzFEIewMLwbl8&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=7&ct=result#PPA236,M1|accessdate=2008-09-23}}</ref> The [[Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games]] (ACOG) also proposed a substantial revenue-sharing with the IOC, USOC, and other NOCs.<ref name=\"Atlanta 1996\">{{cite book|last=Maloney|first=Larry|title=Encyclopedia of the Modern Olympic Movement|editor=Finding, John E. |editor2=Pelle, Kimberly D. |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2004|pages=235\u20136|chapter=Atlanta 1996|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmXi_-Jujj0C&pg=PA236&lpg=PA236&dq=Atlanta+Athens+IOC+bid&source=web&ots=iX4T-9nx6u&sig=N3lyOoVFskaPnXZzFEIewMLwbl8&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=7&ct=result#PPA236,M1|accessdate=2008-09-23}}</ref>\n\n[[Greece]], the home of the [[ancient Olympic Games|ancient]] and [[1896 Summer Olympics|first modern Olympics]], was considered by many observers the \"natural choice\" for the Centennial Games.<ref name=NewYorkTimes90>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/09/19/sports/atlanta-selected-over-athens-for-1996-olympics.html?sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2&pagewanted=print|title=Atlanta Selected Over Athens for 1996 Olympics|last=Weisman|first=Steven R.|date=1990-09-19|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2008-09-23}}</ref><ref name=\"Atlanta 1996\"/> However, Athens bid chairman Spyros Metaxa demanded that it be named as the site of the Olympics because of its \"historical right due to its history\", which may have caused resentment among delegates. Furthermore, the Athens bid was described as \"arrogant and poorly prepared\", being regarded as \"not being up to the task of coping with the modern and risk-prone extravaganza\" of the current Games. Athens faced numerous obstacles, including \"political instability, potential security problems, air pollution, traffic congestion and the fact that it would have to spend about $3 billion to improve its infrastructure of airports, roads, rail lines and other amenities\".<ref name=NewYorkTimes90/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/03/sports/athens-pins-olympic-bid-to-world-meet.html?pagewanted=print|title=Athens Pins Olympic Bid to World Meet|last=Longman|first=Jere|date=1997-08-03|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2008-09-23}}</ref>\n\nAllegations were quick to emerge in the Greek and [[Australia]]n media that Atlanta had won the Games due to a conspiracy organized by global beverage company [[Coca-Cola]], a longtime sponsor of the Olympic Games headquartered in Atlanta. An Athenian daily newspaper declared the \"Olympic flame will not be lit with oil, but with Coca-Cola\", while the Athens bid chair said that the city would never again bid for the Games (a promise that was not carried out eventually, as Athens went on to host the [[2004 Summer Olympics]]). Coca-Cola executives, however, had feared that a successful Atlanta bid would hurt their business. While they produced commemorative pins of the six candidate cities, with the intent of handing out the winning city's pins to IOC delegates, this backfired as others alleged that Coca-Cola had predicted which city had won; indeed sales of the beverage in Greece dropped for the next few years.<ref name=Payne/> A year later, an article appeared in the German periodical ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' accusing the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games (ACOG) of bribing IOC members with up to $120,000 in cash, gold credit cards and college scholarships for their children. In one case, allegations that Atlanta had promised free heart surgery to IOC members coincided with reports that an IOC official had suffered a heart attack while visiting the city, with the medical expenses covered by ACOG as a \"professional courtesy\". In his defense, ACOG Chairman [[Billy Payne]] said, \"Atlanta's bidding effort included excessive actions, even thought processes, that today seem inappropriate but, at the time, reflected the prevailing practices in the selection process and an extremely competitive environment.\" Indeed, these practices were widespread among cities wishing to host an Olympics, right up until the [[2002 Winter Olympic bid scandal|IOC scandal broke in 1998]]. The competing cities spent a total of over $100 million campaigning for the right to host the Summer Games, of which Atlanta spent $7.3 million.<ref name=\"Atlanta 1996\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Olympics bids}}\n\n[[Category:Summer Olympics bids|1996]]\n[[Category:1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:September 1990 events]]\n[[Category:1990 in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Events in Tokyo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Olympic bid|1996|Summer|\n| main = yes\n| Paralympics = yes\n| logo = Atlanta 1996 Olympic bid logo.png\n| logo-size = 175px\n| winner = Atlanta\n| votes1 = 51\n| runner-up = Athens\n| votes2 = 35\n| shortlisted1 = Toronto\n| shortlisted2 = Melbourne\n| shortlisted3 = Manchester\n| shortlisted4 = Belgrade\n| decision = September 18, 1990\n}}\n{{1996 Summer Olympics}}\nSix cities submitted '''bids to host the [[1996 Summer Olympics]]''' (formally known as ''Games of the XXVI Olympiad''), which were awarded to [[Atlanta]], on September 18, 1990. The other candidate cities were [[Athens]] ([[Greece]]), [[Toronto]] ([[Canada]]), [[Melbourne]] ([[Australia]]), [[Manchester]] ([[United Kingdom]]) and [[Belgrade]] ([[FR Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]).\n\n==Results==\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!colspan=7 align=center| 1996 Host City Election \u2014 ballot results\n|-\n! City\n! Country (NOC)\n|bgcolor=silver| '''Round 1'''\n|bgcolor=silver| '''Round 2'''\n|bgcolor=silver| '''Round 3'''\n|bgcolor=silver| '''Round 4'''\n|bgcolor=silver| '''Round 5'''\n|-\n| [[Atlanta]] || {{flag|United States}} || 19 || 20 || '''26''' || '''34''' || '''51'''\n|-\n| [[Athens]] || {{flag|Greece}} || '''23''' || '''23''' || '''26''' || 30 || 35\n|-\n| [[Toronto]] || {{flag|Canada}} || 14 || 17 || 18 || 22 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[Melbourne]] || {{flag|Australia}} || 12 || 21 || 16 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[Manchester]] || {{flag|Great Britain}} || 11 || 5 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[Belgrade]] || {{flag|SFR Yugoslavia}}<ref>The Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia was still in existence at the time of bidding for the 1996 Olympics, although it would cease to exist by the time of the 1996 Summer Olympic games</ref> || 7 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|}\n\n==Background==\nAtlanta was selected by the [[United States Olympic Committee|USOC]] over bids from [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], [[San Francisco]] and runner-up [[Minneapolis]] to be the U.S. representative in international bidding.<ref name=NewYorkTimes88>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/03/29/sports/sports-people-cities-named.html|title=Cities Named|last=|first=|date=1988-03-29|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2012-08-30}}</ref> The city entered the competition as a [[dark horse]], being up against stiff competition.<ref name=Payne>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vqtLnCWHDX0C&pg=PA91 |title=Olympic turnaround: how the Olympic Games stepped back from the brink of Extinction to Become the Best Known Brand|first=Michael|last=Payne|isbn=0-275-99030-3|location=Westport, Ct.|publisher=Praeger Publishers|year=2006}}</ref> The US media also criticized it as a second-tier city and complained of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia's]] [[Georgia in the American Civil War|Confederate history]]. However, the IOC Evaluation Commission ranked Atlanta's infrastructure and facilities the highest, while IOC members said that it could guarantee large television revenues similar to the success of the [[1984 Summer Olympics]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=NewYorkTimes90/> Additionally, former US ambassador to the UN and Atlanta mayor [[Andrew Jackson Young]] touted Atlanta's civil rights history and reputation for racial harmony. Young also wanted to showcase a reformed [[Southern United States|American South]]. The strong economy of Atlanta and improved race relations in the South helped to impress the IOC officials.<ref name=\"Atlanta 1996\">{{cite book|last=Maloney|first=Larry|title=Encyclopedia of the Modern Olympic Movement|editor=Finding, John E. |editor2=Pelle, Kimberly D. |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2004|pages=235\u20136|chapter=Atlanta 1996|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmXi_-Jujj0C&pg=PA236&lpg=PA236&dq=Atlanta+Athens+IOC+bid&source=web&ots=iX4T-9nx6u&sig=N3lyOoVFskaPnXZzFEIewMLwbl8&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=7&ct=result#PPA236,M1|accessdate=2008-09-23}}</ref> The [[Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games]] (ACOG) also proposed a substantial revenue-sharing with the IOC, USOC, and other NOCs.<ref name=\"Atlanta 1996\">{{cite book|last=Maloney|first=Larry|title=Encyclopedia of the Modern Olympic Movement|editor=Finding, John E. |editor2=Pelle, Kimberly D. |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2004|pages=235\u20136|chapter=Atlanta 1996|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmXi_-Jujj0C&pg=PA236&lpg=PA236&dq=Atlanta+Athens+IOC+bid&source=web&ots=iX4T-9nx6u&sig=N3lyOoVFskaPnXZzFEIewMLwbl8&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=7&ct=result#PPA236,M1|accessdate=2008-09-23}}</ref>\n\n[[Greece]], the home of the [[ancient Olympic Games|ancient]] and [[1896 Summer Olympics|first modern Olympics]], was considered by many observers the \"natural choice\" for the Centennial Games.<ref name=NewYorkTimes90>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/09/19/sports/atlanta-selected-over-athens-for-1996-olympics.html?sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2&pagewanted=print|title=Atlanta Selected Over Athens for 1996 Olympics|last=Weisman|first=Steven R.|date=1990-09-19|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2008-09-23}}</ref><ref name=\"Atlanta 1996\"/> However, Athens bid chairman Spyros Metaxa demanded that it be named as the site of the Olympics because of its \"historical right due to its history\", which may have caused resentment among delegates. Furthermore, the Athens bid was described as \"arrogant and poorly prepared\", being regarded as \"not being up to the task of coping with the modern and risk-prone extravaganza\" of the current Games. Athens faced numerous obstacles, including \"political instability, potential security problems, air pollution, traffic congestion and the fact that it would have to spend about $3 billion to improve its infrastructure of airports, roads, rail lines and other amenities\".<ref name=NewYorkTimes90/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/03/sports/athens-pins-olympic-bid-to-world-meet.html?pagewanted=print|title=Athens Pins Olympic Bid to World Meet|last=Longman|first=Jere|date=1997-08-03|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2008-09-23}}</ref>\n\nAllegations were quick to emerge in the Greek and [[Australia]]n media that Atlanta had won the Games due to a conspiracy organized by global beverage company [[Coca-Cola]], a longtime sponsor of the Olympic Games headquartered in Atlanta. An Athenian daily newspaper declared the \"Olympic flame will not be lit with oil, but with Coca-Cola\", while the Athens bid chair said that the city would never again bid for the Games (a promise that was not carried out eventually, as Athens went on to host the [[2004 Summer Olympics]]). Coca-Cola executives, however, had feared that a successful Atlanta bid would hurt their business. While they produced commemorative pins of the six candidate cities, with the intent of handing out the winning city's pins to IOC delegates, this backfired as others alleged that Coca-Cola had predicted which city had won; indeed sales of the beverage in Greece dropped for the next few years.<ref name=Payne/> A year later, an article appeared in the German periodical ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' accusing the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games (ACOG) of bribing IOC members with up to $120,000 in cash, gold credit cards and college scholarships for their children. In one case, allegations that Atlanta had promised free heart surgery to IOC members coincided with reports that an IOC official had suffered a heart attack while visiting the city, with the medical expenses covered by ACOG as a \"professional courtesy\". In his defense, ACOG Chairman [[Billy Payne]] said, \"Atlanta's bidding effort included excessive actions, even thought processes, that today seem inappropriate but, at the time, reflected the prevailing practices in the selection process and an extremely competitive environment.\" Indeed, these practices were widespread among cities wishing to host an Olympics, right up until the [[2002 Winter Olympic bid scandal|IOC scandal broke in 1998]]. The competing cities spent a total of over $100 million campaigning for the right to host the Summer Games, of which Atlanta spent $7.3 million.<ref name=\"Atlanta 1996\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Olympics bids}}\n\n[[Category:Summer Olympics bids|1996]]\n[[Category:1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:September 1990 events]]\n[[Category:1990s in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Events in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:1990s in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bids_for_the_1996_Summer_Olympics"}
{"title_page": "Howie Weinberg", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Howie Weinberg\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         =  <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = [[United States]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = [[Americans|American]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Audio mastering engineer\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Howie Weinberg''' is an [[United States|American]] [[Grammy Award|7X Grammy Award-Winning]] [[Audio mastering|mastering]] engineer with 16 [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] [[Grammy nominated|nominations.]] He has over 200 [[Music recording certification|Gold]] and [[Music recording certification|Platinum]] records.  He has over 19K [[Credit (creative arts)|credits]] according to [[AllMusic]].<ref>[http://www.star-ecentral.com/news/story.asp?file=/2007/11/5/music/19283949&sec=music platinum records]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/howie-weinberg-mn0000828374/credits|title=Howie Weinberg {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> And, holds 4 [[TEC Awards]] and 2 [[Juno Award|Juno Awards.]] \n\n== Career ==\nIn 2011 he moved to [[Los Angeles]] and opened Howie Weinberg Mastering located in [[Laurel Canyon, Los Angeles|Laurel Canyon]] after working at [[Masterdisk]], [[New York City]], since 1977. Weinberg was responsible for the mastering of several [[Bill Laswell]] related releases, such as [[Herbie Hancock]]'s [[Grammy Award]] winning album ''[[Future Shock (Herbie Hancock album)|Future Shock]]'' (including the hit single \"[[Rockit (song)|Rockit]]\"), ''[[Rhythm Killers]]'' by [[Sly and Robbie]], ''[[Brain Drain (album)|Brain Drain]]'' by the [[Ramones]], [[Material (band)|Material]]'s ''[[Memory Serves]]'' and [[Buckethead]]'s debut album ''[[Bucketheadland]]''. Other notable works include the [[Beastie Boys]]' ''[[Licensed to Ill]]'' and the multi-platinum ''[[Nevermind]]'' by [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]] which was [[Grammy nominated]] 6 X with 1 [[Grammy Award|Grammy Award win]].  \n\nHis mastering work on [[Rush (band)|Rush]]'s ''[[Vapor Trails]]'' drew criticism for its [[Loudness war|extremely compressed dynamics]] by the band in 2002. The album, nevertheless, went [[Music recording certification|Gold]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Vapor Trails|date=2019-11-02|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Vapor_Trails&oldid=924168852|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref> \n\nHowie Weinberg currently has over 200 [[Gold Record|Gold & Platinum Records]].  \n\n<blockquote>Once [[Andy Wallace (producer)|Andy Wallace]] had finished his mix of ''Nevermind'', the master tapes were forwarded to Howie Weinberg at Masterdisk Studios in New York City. \"I'm sort of a goal tender in the creative process,\" says Howie Weinberg at Masterdisk Studios in New York. \"I'm the last stop to make it better before pressing.\"</blockquote>\n\nWeinberg also worked with [[Miley Cyrus]], [[Madonna (entertainer)]], [[Grimes (musician)]], [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Van Halen]], [[Tom Waits]], [[The Mars Volta]], [[Spoon (band)|Spoon]], [[Public Enemy (band)|Public Enemy]], [[Yoko Ono]], [[Rammstein]], [[Thirty Seconds to Mars]], [[Metallica]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metallica.com/store/music/cds/13709/master-of-puppets-remastered-cd|title=Master of Puppets (Remastered) - CD - Metallica|website=Metallica|access-date=2017-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830200613/https://www.metallica.com/store/music/cds/13709/master-of-puppets-remastered-cd|archive-date=2017-08-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Aerosmith]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Power|first=Martin|author2=Chris Charlesworth|title=The Complete Guide to the Music of Aerosmith|publisher=Omnibus Press|year=1997|pages=73|isbn=978-0-7119-5598-1}}</ref> 30Aut6<ref>[https://soundcloud.com/30aut6/last-night Soundcloud.com]</ref> and [[The White Stripes]]. [[Dimebag Darrell]] of [[Pantera]] fame is quoted as saying:\n\n<blockquote>When you get to mastering you've got to find the magic mix that works once it goes through all the compression and EQing. We worked with Howie Weinberg and he's a fantabulous motherfucker.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kitts|first=Jeff|title=Guitar World Presents Nu-Metal|publisher=Hal Leonard Publishing Corporation|year=2002|pages=[https://archive.org/details/guitarworldprese00kitt/page/35 35]|isbn=978-0-634-03287-5|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/guitarworldprese00kitt/page/35}}</ref>\n<br /></blockquote>\n\nIn 2003 he mastered [[Grammy Award|Grammy Award Winning,]] [[Sheryl Crow]]'s ''[[Sheryl Crow|C'mon, C'mon]]'' which was released in 2002, spawning the hit single \"[[Soak Up the Sun]]\". The second single, \"Steve McQueen\", which won [[Best Female Rock Vocal Performance]]. The album was 4 X [[Grammy nominated]]. \n\nIn 2006 he won a [[Latin Grammy Award|Latin Grammy]] for [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]] [[Ah\u00ed vamos]] which won for [[Latin Grammy Award|Best Rock Solo Vocal]]. \n\nIn 2008 he won a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] for  [[Grammy Award|mastered]] [[Alive 2007]] by [[Daft Punk]] which won [[Best Electronic/Dance Album]] in 2008. \n\nHe appeared at the 2009 [[South by Southwest|SXSW]] on the Panel: Producers On Making Classic Records.<ref>[http://www.sxsw.com/music/talks/schedule/?action=bio&id=16515 SXSW]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> \n\nIn January 2011, he left Masterdisk to set up his own mastering company in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonicscoop.com/2011/01/08/bidding-farewell-to-howie-weinberg-masterdisk-promotes-matt-agoglia-to-senior-mastering-engineer/|publisher=SonicScoop|title=Bidding Farewell to Howie Weinberg, Masterdisk Promotes Matt Agoglia to Senior Mastering Engineer|date=January 8, 2011|author=Janice Brown|accessdate=2011-02-11}}</ref>.  \n\nIn 2013 he was [[Grammy nominated]] for [[Mastering (audio)|mastered]] [[Fiona Apple]]'s [[The Idler Wheel...]] which was [[Grammy nominated]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Music Album.]]  \n\nin 2017 his work from [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana's]], [[Smells Like Teen Spirit]] , was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]].  \n\nIn 2020 he won [[Grammy Award|3 Grammy's]] for [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]] [[Gary Clark Jr.]]'s album [[This Land (Gary Clark Jr. album)]] which won 3 [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]] and had 4 [[Grammy nominated|Grammy nominations.]] The album won [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Blues Album|Best Contemporary Blues Album]], [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance]], [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song]], and was [[Grammy nominated]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]].   \n\nIn 2020 he also won a [[Latin Grammy Award records|Latin Grammy Award]]  for [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]] [[Mon Laferte]] which won a [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] for [[Best Alternative Music Album]].\n\n== Award ==\nHe has been nominated for the Mix Foundation's [[TEC Awards|Technical Excellence & Creativity award]] for mastering engineer in 1997,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/1997.html|title=1997 TEC Awards winners|accessdate=2009-05-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120914065954/http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/1997.html|archivedate=2012-09-14}}</ref> was part of two of the winners in 2003 (best track with [[Sheryl Crow]]'s \"[[Soak Up the Sun]]\"; best record for Sheryl Crow's ''[[C'mon, C'mon]]''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/03winners.html|title=2003 WINNERS FOR OUTSTANDING TECHNICAL ACHIEVEMENT|accessdate=2009-05-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081027154821/http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/03winners.html|archivedate=2008-10-27}}</ref> and was part of the winners for best track in 2006 with [[Gorillaz]]' \"[[Feel Good Inc.|Feel Good Inc]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/06winners.html|title=2006 TEC Awards Winners|accessdate=2009-05-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606090908/http://mixfoundation.org/tec/06winners.html|archivedate=2009-06-06}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nHowie Weinberg married Rachel Felder, the director of artists and repertory at [[Columbia Records]] in July 1999.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/18/style/weddings-rachel-felder-howie-weinberg.html?sec=&spon=| title=WEDDINGS; Rachel Felder, Howie Weinberg| work=The New York Times| date=July 18, 1999}}</ref>\n\nThe couple separated in 2009 and divorced soon after.\n\n==Partial discography==\nIf not stated otherwise, Howie Weinberg received credits for mastering and listed in alphabetical order:\n\n* [[...And You Will Know Us by the Trail of Dead]] - ''[[Source Tags & Codes]]'' (2002)\n* [[13 Engines]] - ''Perpetual Motion Machine'' (1993)\n* [[24-7 Spyz]] - ''[[Heavy Metal Soul by the Pound]]'' (1996)\n* [[2nd II None]] - [[2nd II None (album)|''2nd II None'']] (1991)\n* [[3 Doors Down]] - ''[[Seventeen Days]]'' (2005)\n* [[3 Colours Red]] - ''[[The Union of Souls]]'' (2004)\n* [[3rd Bass]] - ''[[The Cactus Album]]'' (1989), ''[[Derelicts of Dialect]]'' (1991)\n* [[54-40 (band)|54-40]] - ''[[Since When]]'' (1998)\n* [[7horse]] - ''Songs for a Voodoo Wedding'' (2014); ''Livin in a Bitch of a World'' (2016)\n* [[A Dozen Furies]] - ''[[A Concept from Fire]]'' (2005)\n