o Birds Sing?]]'' (1991); ''[[Freak Magnet]]'' (2000)\n* [[Ween]] - ''[[Pure Guava]]'' (1992); ''[[Chocolate and Cheese]]'' (1994); ''[[White Pepper]]'' (2000); [[Quebec (album)|''Quebec'']] (2003); [[La Cucaracha (album)|''La Cucaracha'']] (2007)\n* [[The White Stripes]] - ''[[Get Behind Me Satan]]'' (2005)\n* Xu Xu Fang - ''Daylong Secret'' (2016)\n* [[Xzibit]] - ''[[Napalm (album)|Napalm]]'' (2012)\n* [[Yeah Yeah Yeahs]] - ''[[Fever to Tell]]'' (2003); ''[[Show Your Bones]]'' (2006)\n* [[Young Guns (band)|Young Guns]] - ''[[Ones and Zeros (Young Guns album)|Ones and Zeros]]'' (2015)\n* [[Zwan]] - ''[[Mary Star of the Sea (album)|Mary Star of the Sea]]'' (2003)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.howieweinbergmastering.com Official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100206033155/http://www.masterdisk.com/engineers/engineer.php?id=26&page=b Howie Weinberg's bio at Masterdisk]\n* {{discogs artist}}\n* [http://www.trht.net/artist/Howie+Weinberg ''Howie Weinberg'', The Rock Hard Times]\n*https://www.allmusic.com/artist/howie-weinberg-mn0000828374/credits\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weinberg, Howie}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Mastering engineers]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American audio engineer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Howie Weinberg\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         =  <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = [[United States]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place   =\n| nationality   = [[Americans|American]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Audio mastering engineer\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Howie Weinberg''' is an [[United States|American]] [[Grammy Award|7X Grammy Award-Winning]] [[Audio mastering|mastering]] engineer with 10 [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] [[Grammy nominated|nominations.]] He has over 200 [[Music recording certification|Gold]] and [[Music recording certification|Platinum]] records.  He has over 19K [[Credit (creative arts)|credits]] according to [[AllMusic]].<ref>[http://www.star-ecentral.com/news/story.asp?file=/2007/11/5/music/19283949&sec=music platinum records]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/howie-weinberg-mn0000828374/credits|title=Howie Weinberg {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> And, holds 4 [[TEC Awards]] and 2 [[Juno Award|Juno Awards.]] \n\n== Career ==\nIn 2011 he moved to [[Los Angeles]] and opened Howie Weinberg Mastering located in [[Laurel Canyon, Los Angeles|Laurel Canyon]] after working at [[Masterdisk]], [[New York City]], since 1977. Weinberg was responsible for the mastering of several [[Bill Laswell]] related releases, such as [[Herbie Hancock]]'s [[Grammy Award]] winning album ''[[Future Shock (Herbie Hancock album)|Future Shock]]'' (including the hit single \"[[Rockit (song)|Rockit]]\"), ''[[Rhythm Killers]]'' by [[Sly and Robbie]], ''[[Brain Drain (album)|Brain Drain]]'' by the [[Ramones]], [[Material (band)|Material]]'s ''[[Memory Serves]]'' and [[Buckethead]]'s debut album ''[[Bucketheadland]]''. Other notable works include the [[Beastie Boys]]' ''[[Licensed to Ill]]'' and the multi-platinum ''[[Nevermind]]'' by [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]].  His mastering work on [[Rush (band)|Rush]]'s ''[[Vapor Trails]]'' drew criticism for its [[Loudness war|extremely compressed dynamics]] by the band. The album, nevertheless, went [[Music recording certification|Gold]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Vapor Trails|date=2019-11-02|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Vapor_Trails&oldid=924168852|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>  \n\n<blockquote>Once [[Andy Wallace (producer)|Andy Wallace]] had finished his mix of ''Nevermind'', the master tapes were forwarded to Howie Weinberg at Masterdisk Studios in New York City. \"I'm sort of a goal tender in the creative process,\" says Howie Weinberg at Masterdisk Studios in New York. \"I'm the last stop to make it better before pressing.\"</blockquote>\n\nWeinberg also worked with [[Chance the Rapper]], [[Van Halen]], [[Tom Waits]], [[The Mars Volta]], [[Spoon (band)|Spoon]], [[Public Enemy (band)|Public Enemy]], [[Rammstein]], [[Thirty Seconds to Mars]], [[Metallica]],<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metallica.com/store/music/cds/13709/master-of-puppets-remastered-cd|title=Master of Puppets (Remastered) - CD - Metallica|website=Metallica|access-date=2017-08-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830200613/https://www.metallica.com/store/music/cds/13709/master-of-puppets-remastered-cd|archive-date=2017-08-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Aerosmith]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Power|first=Martin|author2=Chris Charlesworth|title=The Complete Guide to the Music of Aerosmith|publisher=Omnibus Press|year=1997|pages=73|isbn=978-0-7119-5598-1}}</ref> 30Aut6<ref>[https://soundcloud.com/30aut6/last-night Soundcloud.com]</ref> and [[The White Stripes]]. [[Dimebag Darrell]] of [[Pantera]] fame is quoted as saying:\n\n<blockquote>When you get to mastering you've got to find the magic mix that works once it goes through all the compression and EQing. We worked with Howie Weinberg and he's a fantabulous motherfucker.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kitts|first=Jeff|title=Guitar World Presents Nu-Metal|publisher=Hal Leonard Publishing Corporation|year=2002|pages=[https://archive.org/details/guitarworldprese00kitt/page/35 35]|isbn=978-0-634-03287-5|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/guitarworldprese00kitt/page/35}}</ref>\n<br /></blockquote>\n\nIn 2006 he [[Mastering (audio)|mastered]] [[Ah\u00ed vamos]] which won a [[Latin Grammy Award|Latin Grammy]] for [[Latin Grammy Award|Best Rock Solo Vocal]]. \n\nIn 2007 he [[Mastering (audio)|mastered]] [[Alive 2007]] by [[Daft Punk]] which won a Grammy [[Best Electronic/Dance Album]] in 2008. \n\nHe appeared at the 2009 [[South by Southwest|SXSW]] on the Panel: Producers On Making Classic Records.<ref>[http://www.sxsw.com/music/talks/schedule/?action=bio&id=16515 SXSW]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> \n\nIn January 2011, he left Masterdisk to set up his own mastering company in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonicscoop.com/2011/01/08/bidding-farewell-to-howie-weinberg-masterdisk-promotes-matt-agoglia-to-senior-mastering-engineer/|publisher=SonicScoop|title=Bidding Farewell to Howie Weinberg, Masterdisk Promotes Matt Agoglia to Senior Mastering Engineer|date=January 8, 2011|author=Janice Brown|accessdate=2011-02-11}}</ref>.  \n\nIn 2020 he won [[Grammy Award|3 Grammy wins]] for [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]] [[Gary Clark Jr.]]'s album [[This Land (Gary Clark Jr. album)]] which won 3 [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]] and had 4 [[Grammy nominated|Grammy nominations.]] The album won [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Blues Album|Best Contemporary Blues Album]], [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance]], [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song]], and was [[Grammy nominated]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]].\n\nIn 2020 also won a [[Latin Grammy Award records|Latin Grammy Award]]  for [[Mastering (audio)|mastering]] [[Mon Laferte]] which won a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best Alternative Music Album]].  \n\n== Award ==\nHe has been nominated for the Mix Foundation's [[TEC Awards|Technical Excellence & Creativity award]] for mastering engineer in 1997,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/1997.html|title=1997 TEC Awards winners|accessdate=2009-05-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120914065954/http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/1997.html|archivedate=2012-09-14}}</ref> was part of two of the winners in 2003 (best track with [[Sheryl Crow]]'s \"[[Soak Up the Sun]]\"; best record for Sheryl Crow's ''[[C'mon, C'mon]]''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/03winners.html|title=2003 WINNERS FOR OUTSTANDING TECHNICAL ACHIEVEMENT|accessdate=2009-05-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081027154821/http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/03winners.html|archivedate=2008-10-27}}</ref> and was part of the winners for best track in 2006 with [[Gorillaz]]' \"[[Feel Good Inc.|Feel Good Inc]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixfoundation.org/tec/06winners.html|title=2006 TEC Awards Winners|accessdate=2009-05-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606090908/http://mixfoundation.org/tec/06winners.html|archivedate=2009-06-06}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nHowie Weinberg married Rachel Felder, the director of artists and repertory at [[Columbia Records]] in July 1999.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/18/style/weddings-rachel-felder-howie-weinberg.html?sec=&spon=| title=WEDDINGS; Rachel Felder, Howie Weinberg| work=The New York Times| date=July 18, 1999}}</ref>\n\nThe couple separated in 2009 and divorced soon after.\n\n==Partial discography==\nIf not stated otherwise, Howie Weinberg received credits for mastering\n*[[This Land (Gary Clark Jr. album)]] (2019)\n*[[Foster the People]] - [[Pumped Up Kicks|\"Pumped Up Kicks\"]] (2010)\n* [[...And You Will Know Us by the Trail of Dead]] - ''[[Source Tags & Codes]]'' (2002)\n* [[13 Engines]] - ''Perpetual Motion Machine'' (1993)\n* [[24-7 Spyz]] - ''[[Heavy Metal Soul by the Pound]]'' (1996)\n* [[2nd II None]] - [[2nd II None (album)|''2nd II None'']] (1991)\n* [[3 Doors Down]] - ''[[Seventeen Days]]'' (2005)\n* [[3 Colours Red]] - ''[[The Union of Souls]]'' (2004)\n* [[3rd Bass]] - ''[[The Cactus Album]]'' (1989), ''[[Derelicts of Dialect]]'' (1991)\n* [[54-40 (band)|54-40]] - ''[[Since When]]'' (1998)\n* [[7horse]] - ''Songs for a Voodoo Wedding'' (2014); ''Livin in a Bitch of a World'' (2016)\n* [[A Dozen Furies]] - ''[[A Concept from Fire]]'' (2005)\n* [[A Giant Dog]] - ''Pile'' (2016)\n* [[A Perfect Murder (band)|A Perfect Murder]] - [[Unbroken (A Perfect Murder album)|''Unbroken'']] (2004); ''[[Strength Through Vengeance]]'' (2005)\n* [[A (band)|A]] - [['A' vs. Monkey Kong|''<nowiki/>'A' vs. Monkey Kong'']] (2000)\n* [[Abiodun Oyewole]] - ''25 Years'' (1996)\n* [[Acid Test (band)|Acid Test]] - ''Drop'' (1993)\n* [[Active Child]] - ''You Are All I See'' (2011); ''Rapor'' (2013)\n* [[Adele Bertei]] - ''Little Lives'' (1988)\n* [[Aerosmith]] - ''[[Done with Mirrors]]'' (1985)\n* [[After the Fall (band)|After the Fall]] - ''[[Always Forever Now]]'' (2005)\n* [[Alabama 3]] - ''[[Exile on Coldharbour Lane]]'' (1997)\n* [[Aleks Syntek]] - ''[[89\u201399]]'' (2000)\n* [[Alice Cooper]] - [[The Last Temptation (Alice Cooper album)|''The Last Temptation'']] (1994)\n* [[Alien Crime Syndicate]] - ''[[Dust to Dirt]]'' (2000); ''[[From the Word Go]]'' (2000); ''[[Ten Songs in the Key of Betrayal]]'' (2004)\n* [[All Hail the Yeti]] - ''All Hail the Yeti'' (2012)\n* [[The Almighty (band)|The Almighty]] - ''[[Psycho-Narco]]'' (2001)\n* [[AM Taxi]] - ''We Don't Stand a Chance'' (2010)\n* [[American Hi-Fi]] - ''[[Blood & Lemonade]]'' (2014)\n* [[Amusement Parks on Fire]] - ''Out of the Angeles'' (2005)\n* [[Andrew Dice Clay]] - ''[[40 Too Long]]'' (1993)\n* [[Andrew W.K.]] - ''[[I Get Wet]]'' (2001); [[The Wolf (Andrew W.K. album)|''The Wolf'']] (2003)\n* [[Angelo Badalamenti]] - ''[[Soundtrack from Twin Peaks]]'' (1990)\n* [[Antenna (band)|Antenna]] - [[Hideout (album)|''Hideout'']] (1993)\n* [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] - ''[[Spreading the Disease]]'' (1985)\n* [[Anti-Flag]] - ''[[For Blood and Empire]]'' (2006)\n* [[Apoptygma Berzerk]] - ''[[Rocket Science (Apoptygma Berzerk album)|Rocket Science]]'' (2009)\n* [[Arctic Monkeys]] - [[Humbug (album)|''Humbug'']] (2009)\n* [[Arid (band)|Arid]] - ''[[Little Things of Venom]]'' (2000)\n* [[Arlen Roth]] - ''Arlen Roth'' (1987)\n* [[Arrested Development (group)|Arrested Development]] - ''[[3 Years, 5 Months & 2 Days in the Life Of...]]'' (1992); ''[[Zingalamaduni]]'' (1994)\n* [[Arsonists (hip hop group)|Arsonists]] - ''[[As the World Burns]]'' (1999)\n* [[Art Bergmann]] - ''[[Crawl with Me]]'' (1988); [[Art Bergmann (album)|''Art Bergmann'']] (1991)\n* [[Arto Lindsay]] - ''[[Mundo Civilizado]]'' (1996)\n* [[Ash (band)|Ash]] - [[Meltdown (Ash album)|''Meltdown'']] (2004)\n* [[Atreyu]] - [[The Curse (Atreyu album)|''The Curse'']] (2004); ''[[Lead Sails Paper Anchor]]'' (2007); [[Long Live (Atreyu album)|''Long Live'']] (2015)\n* [[Authority Zero]] - [[Andiamo (album)|''Andiamo'']] (2004)\n* [[Autopilot Off]] - [[Autopilot Off (EP)|''Autopilot Off'']] (2002); ''[[Make a Sound]]'' (2004)\n* [[Awaken the Empire]] - ''Aurora'' (2015)\n* [[Axel Bauer]] - ''Simple Mortel'' (1998)\n* [[B'z]] - [[Action (B'z album)|''Action'']] (2007)\n* [[Babas\u00f3nicos]] - ''[[Dop\u00e1dromo]]'' (1996); [[Miami (Babas\u00f3nicos album)|''Miami'']] (2000); ''[[Jessico]]'' (2002); [[Infame (album)|''Infame'']] (2004)\n* [[Babe the Blue Ox (band)|Babe the Blue Ox]] - ''People'' (1996)\n* [[Baby Chaos]] - ''Safe Sex Designer Drugs & the Death of Rock 'n' Roll'' (1995)\n* [[Babylon A.D. (band)|Babylon A.D.]] - ''Nothing Sacred'' (1992)\n* [[Bad Brains]] - [[Rise (Bad Brains album)|''Rise'']] (1993); ''[[Black Dots]]'' (1996)\n* [[Barkmarket]] - ''[[Vegas Throat]]'' (1990); [[Gimmick (album)|''Gimmick'']] (1993)\n* [[Barrington Levy]] - ''Turning Point'' (1992)\n* [[Beastie Boys]] - ''[[Licensed to Ill]]'' (1986)